This, which you do in the `error` body later:

```
+    if (env && env_count >= 0)
 +        psutil_free_cstrings_array(env, env_count);
 +
 +    Py_XDECREF(py_envname);
 +    Py_XDECREF(py_envval);
 +    Py_XDECREF(py_retdict);
 +    return NULL;
```

As a general rule you should only define one "error" goto block, not different gotos, and implement the whole free resource logic in there (in 1 place only). Apply this construct everywhere. It's safer and also consistent with the existent code base.

`IDisableCSRFProtection` was introduced in `plone.protect = 2.x`.
So testing whether `plone.protect` is there is not really helping here, because if it is an `1.x` version it will still fail.

So I could do that:
```python
try:
    pkg_resources.get_distribution('plone.protect')
except pkg_resources.DistributionNotFound:
    DISABLE_CSRF = False
else:
    try:
        from plone.protect.interfaces import IDisableCSRFProtection
    except ImportError:
        DISABLE_CSRF = False
    else:
        DISABLE_CSRF = True
```
but then again...
:wink:

I don't think we should change this. Because we need to call `encode()` when `unicode` object is passed with Python 2 to this method.
How about this?
```
PY3 = sys.version_info > (3, 0, 0)

@staticmethod
def unicode2utf8(text):
    if PY3:
        return text

    if isinstance(text, unicode):
        return text.encode('utf-8')
```

@oshtaier This will return every single organization:

    GET /katello/api/v2/organizations
    {'name': 'foo'}

This will return all organizations with a name (equaling? like? containing?) foo:

    GET /katello/api/v2/organizations
    {'search': 'name=foo'}

This will return no organizations at all:

    GET /katello/api/v2/organizations
    {'search': 'name:foo'}

The search syntax is undefined, no errors are ever returned when an invalid search is submitted, and exactly which fields can be submitted in an outer hash versus an inner "search" hash varies on a per-URL basis.

So yes, providing a name is sufficient to find a particular organization. But how do you provide that name to the API? Not in a way that you might expect.

